{{refimprove|date=October 2015}} {{Infobox oil refinery | name = Abadan Refinery | image = Abadan Catalitic facilities.jpg | image alt = | caption = Abadan Refinery, 1970 | location_map = | location_map_width = | location_map_text = | coordinates = | coordinates_ref = | country = [[Iran]] | province = | city = [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]] | operator = | owner = | founded = {{Start date|1912}} | closure = | capacity = | capacity bbl/d = 429000 | employees = | ref units = | oil tank = | oil refining center = }} The '''Abadan refinery''' ({{lang-fa|پالایشگاه آبادان}} ''Pālāyeshgāh-e Ābādān'') is located in [[Abadan, Iran|Abadan]] near the coast of the [[Persian Gulf]]. Built by the [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company]] (later [[BP]]), it was completed in 1912 and was one of world's largest [[oil refinery|oil refineries]]. Its [[Anglo-Persian Oil Company#Nationalisation and coup|nationalisation in 1951]] prompted the [[Abadan Crisis]] and ultimately the [[1953 Iranian coup d'état|toppling]] of the democratically elected<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/56651387|title=Iran|last=Kamin.|first=Mohammadi,|last2=1963-|first2=Elliott, Mark,|date=2004-01-01|publisher=Lonely Planet|isbn=1740594258|oclc=56651387}}</ref> prime minister [[Mohammad Mosaddegh|Mossaddegh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/center-for-the-study-of-intelligence/csi-publications/csi-studies/studies/vol48no2/article10.html|title=All the Shah's Men: An American Coup and the Roots of Middle East Terror — Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=2017-01-08}}</ref>
The refinery was largely destroyed in September 1980 by Iraq during the initial stages of the Iraqi invasion of Iran's [[Khuzestan]] province, triggering the [[Iraq-Iran war]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}. It had a capacity of 635,000 b/d in 1980 and formed a [[oil refineries|refinery complex]] with important [[petrochemical]] plants. Its capacity has been increased steadily since the war ended in 1988 and is now listed as {{convert|429000|oilbbl/d}} of crude oil.<ref>http://www.abadan-ref.ir/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12&Itemid=84 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725211827/http://www.abadan-ref.ir/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=12&Itemid=84 |date=2014-07-25 }}</ref>
In December 2017, [[Sinopec]] signed a $1 billion deal to expand the Abadan refinery.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sinopec Signs $1b Abadan Refinery Expansion Deal|url=https://financialtribune.com/articles/energy/78896/sinopec-signs-1b-abadan-refinery-expansion-deal|website=Financial Tribune|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>
