'''Idrialin''' is a [[mineral]] [[wax]] which can be distilled from the mineral [[idrialite]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=QBdPdPaOQKMC&pg=PA749&lpg=PA749&dq=idrialin&source=bl&ots=2llV1wfnaC&sig=A1mKtDzwmvihwL5KVPCLj9bLxXo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwilxMjQ3IrbAhWE94MKHffyAcgQ6AEIZDAN#v=onepage&q=idrialin&f=false|title=Chemistry of Organic Bodies: Vegetables|last=Thomson|first=Thomas|date=1838|publisher=Maclachlan & Stewart|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=748|language=en}}</ref> According to G. Goldschmidt of the [[Chemical Society|Chemical Society of London]], it can be extracted by means of [[xylene]], [[amyl alcohol]] or [[turpentine]]; also without decomposition, by distillation in a current of [[hydrogen]], or [[carbon dioxide]]. It is a white crystalline body, very difficultly fusible, boiling above 440&nbsp;°C (824&nbsp;°F). Its solution in glacial [[acetic acid]], by oxidation with [[chromic acid]], yielded a red powdery solid and a [[fatty acid]] fusing at 62&nbsp;°C, and exhibiting all the characters of a mixture of [[palmitic acid]] and [[stearic acid]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=QbZLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA167&dq=idrialin&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAmPLW3IrbAhUI44MKHeh9BgQQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q=idrialin&f=false|title=Journal of the Chemical Society|last=Goldschmidt|first=G.|publisher=The Chemical Society of London|year=1879|isbn=|editor-last=Watts|editor-first=Henry|location=|pages=167|language=en}}</ref>

